ay World", "url": "https://www.academia.edu/Documents/in/Malay_World?f_ri=1383602", "nofollow": false}, {"id": 26064, "name": "Philippine History", "url": "https://www.academia.edu/Documents/in/Philippine_History?f_ri=1383602", "nofollow": false}, {"id": 38394, "name": "Nusantara", "url": "https://www.academia.edu/Documents/in/Nusantara?f_ri=1383602"}, {"id": 215532, "name": "Jose Rizal", "url": "https://www.academia.edu/Documents/in/Jose_Rizal?f_ri=1383602"}, {"id": 419516, "name": "Indentity Studies", "url": "https://www.academia.edu/Documents/in/Indentity_Studies?f_ri=1383602"}, {"id": 517452, "name": "Filipinos", "url": "https://www.academia.edu/Documents/in/Filipinos?f_ri=1383602"}, {"id": 563177, "name": "Filipino Identity", "url": "https://www.academia.edu/Documents/in/Filipino_Identity?f_ri=1383602"}, {"id": 921816, "name": "Hispanization of the Phiippines", "url": "https://www.academia.edu/Documents/in/Hispanization_of_the_Phiippines?f_ri=1383602"}, {"id": 1383602, "name": "Malayness", "url": "https://www.academia.edu/Documents/in/Malayness?f_ri=1383602"}]}, {"id": 10084819, "title": "(2015). Thailand\u2019s Muslim mosaic between Central Plains and Far\u2010south - Grounded perspectives from the Sufi margins. ", "created_at": "2015-01-09T03:42:50.042-08:00", "url": "https://www.academia.edu/10084819/_2015_Thailand_s_Muslim_mosaic_between_Central_Plains_and_Far_south_Grounded_perspectives_from_the_Sufi_margins?f_ri=1383602", "dom_id": "work_10084819", "summary": "Although historically influenced by Theravada Buddhist for more than a millennium, Thailand\u2019s ethnic, linguistic, and religious homogeneity has been over-asserted by state-makers, and erroneously assumed by some scholars. After descendants of Chinese immigrants, widely regarded as Thailand\u2019s largest and most successfully assimilated ethnic minority, Malays residing south of Satun and Songkhla are over three times more numerous that the Northern Khmer of southern Isaan, its next most populous ethnic minority. Practically all Thai citizens self-identifying as Melayu are Muslims, and Islam is Thailand\u2019s largest religious minority. Nevertheless, not all Muslims self-identify as Malays, and Islam has long been acknowledged as being anything but a monolith. In addition to being an ethnically diverse ecumene, its sectarian divisions mirror those present throughout Southeast Asia. Some surmise Thailand\u2019s Muslims being divided between \u201cMalay-Muslims\u201d, and \u201cThai-Muslims\u201d who are either traditionalist or reformist in orientation. This paper proposes perspectives on Thailand\u2019s Muslim mosaic based multi-sited fieldwork among Sufi orders (Ar. turuq, tariqa [sg.]) with visible and viable followings from among the Central Thai-speaking, Southern Thai-speaking, and Malay-speaking Muslim communities. This paper seeks to articulate alternatives to the double-barreled binaries that have provided the theoretical ballast in previous explorations of Muslim ethnic and religious diversity. Whilst relevant details of these hereunto unstudied Sufi orders are provided, this paper\u2019s considers the significance of their presence in three cultural milieu between Ayutthaya and Narathiwat over the details of the spiritual lineages (Ar. silsilah) or litanies (Ar. wird) of individual orders. Rather than where these orders have come from, I concentrate on both their adoption by Central Thai, Southern Thailand, and Malay-speaking Muslims, and the manner in which they have been adapted in ways that reflect these regional identities. Most tariqa might remain within the cultural milieu where they have been localized, but boundaries between these are far from fixed.", "downloadable_attachments": [{"id": 36208298, "asset_id": 10084819, "asset_type": "Work", "always_allow_download": false}], "ordered_authors": [{"id": 667449, "first_name": "Christopher", "last_name": "Joll", "domain_name": "victoria", "page_name": "ChristopherJoll", "display_name": "Chri