yness", "url": "https://www.academia.edu/Documents/in/Malayness?f_ri=1383602"}, {"id": 1750941, "name": "Muslims in South Thailand", "url": "https://www.academia.edu/Documents/in/Muslims_in_South_Thailand?f_ri=1383602"}]}, {"id": 68465124, "title": "The Strength of Malayness Through Colonial Mimicry in Affifudin Omar\u2019s Tun Tuah", "created_at": "2022-01-16T20:15:11.428-08:00", "url": "https://www.academia.edu/68465124/The_Strength_of_Malayness_Through_Colonial_Mimicry_in_Affifudin_Omar_s_Tun_Tuah?f_ri=1383602", "dom_id": "work_68465124", "summary": "The research on Homi Bhabha\u2019s theory of mimicry in postcolonial literature is no longer new. However, in Malay literature, the application of mimicry in order to analyse such fiction is still rare. This paper seeks to utilise the conceptual framework of Homi K. Bhabha\u2019s colonial mimicry in order to explain the portrayal of the Malay characters in Tun Tuah and eventually analyse the characters\u2019 strength in terms of their Malayness in critical situations or crises. The conceptual framework have been explicated into three major parts for the analysis of the novels in terms of; a) contesting colonisation, b) metonymy of presence, and c) resisting colonialist discourse. Excerpts from the novels will be extracted and presented for analysis under each part of the conceptual framework as mentioned above. A close reading of Tun Tuah will be applied as methodology to explore how the strong Malay characters could be divided into either those who mimic the people of the West, those who truly fi...", "downloadable_attachments": [{"id": 78931160, "asset_id": 68465124, "asset_type": "Work", "always_allow_download": false}], "ordered_authors": [{"id": 7907144, "first_name": "Nurhanis", "last_name": "Sahiddan", "domain_name": "uniten", "page_name": "NurhanisSahiddan", "display_name": "Nurhanis Sahiddan", "profile_url": "https://uniten.academia.edu/NurhanisSahiddan?f_ri=1383602", "photo": "https://0.academia-photos.com/7907144/2786648/60045884/s65_nurhanis.sahiddan.png"}, {"id": 19684131, "first_name": "Tengku Intan Marlina", "last_name": "Tengku Mohd Ali", "domain_name": "malaya", "page_name": "TengkuIntanMarlina", "display_name": "Tengku Intan Marlina  Tengku Mohd Ali", "profile_url": "https://malaya.academia.edu/TengkuIntanMarlina?f_ri=1383602", "photo": "https://0.academia-photos.com/19684131/5673952/6454961/s65_elyna.hasnulnawi.jpg"}, {"id": 188100140, "first_name": "HASHIM", "last_name": "ISMAIL", "domain_name": "independent", "page_name": "HASHIMISMAIL16", "display_name": "HASHIM ISMAIL", "profile_url": "https://independent.academia.edu/HASHIMISMAIL16?f_ri=1383602", "photo": "/images/s65_no_pic.png"}], "research_interests": [{"id": 2860, "name": "Postcolonial Studies", "url": "https://www.academia.edu/Documents/in/Postcolonial_Studies?f_ri=1383602", "nofollow": false}, {"id": 13995, "name": "Postcolonial Theory", "url": "https://www.academia.edu/Documents/in/Postcolonial_Theory?f_ri=1383602", "nofollow": false}, {"id": 30045, "name": "Homi Bhabha (Cultural Theory)", "url": "https://www.academia.edu/Documents/in/Homi_Bhabha_Cultural_Theory_?f_ri=1383602", "nofollow": false}, {"id": 179294, "name": "Mimicry", "url": "https://www.academia.edu/Documents/in/Mimicry?f_ri=1383602", "nofollow": false}, {"id": 313099, "name": "Malay literature", "url": "https://www.academia.edu/Documents/in/Malay_literature?f_ri=1383602"}, {"id": 981355, "name": "Malay Identity", "url": "https://www.academia.edu/Documents/in/Malay_Identity?f_ri=1383602"}, {"id": 1383602, "name": "Malayness", "url": "https://www.academia.edu/Documents/in/Malayness?f_ri=1383602"}, {"id": 4077694, "name": "malay novel", "url": "https://www.academia.edu/Documents/in/malay_novel?f_ri=1383602"}, {"id": 4077695, "name": "affifudin omar", "url": "https://www.academia.edu/Documents/in/affifudin_omar?f_ri=1383602"}]}, {"id": 68465122, "title": "Gauging The Enemy in the Blanket Through the Paradigm of Malayness", "created_at": "2022-01-16T20:15:11.217-08:00", "url": "https://www.academia.edu/68465122/Gauging_The_Enemy_in_the_Blanket_Through_the_Paradigm_of_Malayness?f_ri=1383602", "dom_id": "work_68465122", "summary": "Anthony Burgess (1917 - 1993) has written a trilogy of novels on the Malay World, namely The Malayan Trilogy (1964). It has been suggested that the trilogy, which consists of the novels Time for a Tiger (1956), The Enemy in the Blanket (1958) and Beds in the East (1959), depicts the Islamic practices through its Muslim Malay characters, displaying their hypocrisy and their wayward Islamic practices as stated by Zawiyah Yahya (2003). In contrast, the trilogy has rarely been studied based on elements of the paradigm of Malayness in literature, consisting of six elements, namely the Malay language, Islam, the Malay rulers, adat/culture, ethnicity, and identity. Therefore, we aim to analyse one of the novels in the trilogy, The Enemy in the Blanket, in light of Islam as one of the elements under the paradigm of Malayness in literature as stated by Ida as our primary conceptual framework in this study. To achieve these objectives, we employ a close textual reading on the novel by analysing the Muslim Malay characters in The Enemy in the Blanket. The findings show that the Muslim Malay characters in The Enemy in the Blanket could be considered as wayward Muslims in their practices and beliefs. Therefore, we would like to reconfirm that the paradigm of Malayness in in fact, an everyday- defined social reality, as experienced by the people in the course of their everyday life as opposed to it as an authority-defined social reality, as defined by people of the dominant power structure. It is hoped that this study will contribute to the on-going discourse on Islam as the paradigm of Malayness as well as English literature on the Malay World.", "downloadable_attachments": [{"id": 78930471, "asset_id": 68465122, "asset_type": "Work", "always_allow_download": false}], "ordered_authors": [{"id": 7907144, "first_name": "Nurhanis", "last_name": "Sahiddan", "domain_name": "uniten", "page_name": "NurhanisSahiddan", "display_name": "Nurhanis Sahiddan", "profile_url": "https://uniten.academia.edu/NurhanisSahiddan?f_ri=1383602", "photo": "https://0.academia-photos.com/7907144/2786648/60045884/s65_nurhanis.sahiddan.png"}, {"id": 252341, "first_name": "Mastura", "last_name": "Johar", "domain_name": "putrabusinessschool", "page_name": "MasJohar", "display_name": "Mastura  Johar", "profile_url": "https://putrabusinessschool.academia.edu/MasJohar?f_ri=1383602", "photo": "/images/s65_no_pic.png"}], "research_interests": [{"id": 184, "name": "Sociology", "url": "https://www.academia.edu/Documents/in/Sociology?f_ri=1383602", "nofollow": false}, {"id": 2860, "name": "Postcolonial Studies", "url": "https://www.academia.edu/Documents/in/Postcolonial_Studies?f_ri=1383602", "nofollow": false}, {"id": 15863, "name": "Postcolonial Literature", "url": "https://www.academia.edu/Documents/in/Postcolonial_Literature?f_ri=1383602", "nofollow": false}, {"id": 74382, "name": "Novels", "url": "https://www.academia.edu/Documents/in/Novels?f_ri=1383602", "nofollow": false}, {"id": 981355, "name": "Malay Identity", "url": "https://www.academia.edu/Documents/in/Malay_Identity?f_ri=1383602"}, {"id": 1383602, "name": "Malayness", "url": "https://www.academia.edu/Documents/in/Malayness?f_ri=1383602"}]}, {"id": 44355722, "title": "Manufacturing Malayness: British debates on the Malay nation, civilisation, race and language in the early nineteenth century", "created_at": "2020-10-23T04:54:54.640-07:00", "url": "https://www.academia.edu/44355722/Manufacturing_Malayness_British_debates_on_the_Malay_nation_civilisation_race_and_language_in_the_early_nineteenth_century?f_ri=1383602", "dom_id": "work_44355722", "summary": "This article examines the ways in which the notion of Malayness was conceptualised, articulated, and debated in a set of foundational British discourses on this topic during the first two decades of the nineteenth century. Using T.R. Trautmann's concept of locational techniques and D. Rowly-Conwy's idea of competing referential frameworks, the article argues that these conceptualisations have to be assessed within their contemporary colonial and epistemic contexts. The differences in the ascribed importance of language, nation, race, and civilisation in the definition of Malayness thus depended upon whether it was inscribed into a framework composed of orientalist philology, Scottish Enlightenment theories of stadial progress or a genealogically infused ethnology. Applying evidence procured from the fields of textual philology, comparative philology, racial classification, antiquarianism, and conjectural history, the scholar-administrators William Marsden, John Leyden, Stamford Raffles, and John Crawfurd offered their discrepant versions of Malay origin, history, and essence. These versions each embodied their own particular historical vision that not merely prefigured the authoritative mode of approaching and assessing the notion of Malayness, but it also prescribed the scope within which the imperial politics could be framed and the colonial projects unrolled.\n\nKeywords: Colonial discourses, British ideas on Malayness, science, history, and ideology, early nineteenth century, colonial Southeast Asia", "downloadable_attachments": [{"id": 64750266, "asset_id": 44355722, "asset_type": "Work", "always_allow_download": false}], "ordered_authors": [{"id": 20400995, "first_name": "Martin", "last_name": "M\u00fcller", "domain_name": "ku-dk", "page_name": "MartinM\u00fcller", "display_name": "Martin M\u00fcller", "profile_url": "https://ku-dk.academia.edu/MartinM%C3%BCller?f_ri=1383602", "photo": "https://0.academia-photos.com/20400995/48709368/36893085/s65_martin.m_ller.jpg"}], "research_interests": [{"id": 95, "name": "History of Linguistics", "url": "https://www.academia.edu/Documents/in/History_of_Linguistics?f_ri=1383602", "nofollow": false}, {"id": 135, "name": "Intellectual History", "url": "https://www.academia.edu/Documents/in/Intellectual_History?f_ri=1383602", "nofollow": false}, {"id": 4996, "name": "History of Anthropology", "url": "https://www.academia.edu/Documents/in/History_of_Anthropology?f_ri=1383602", "nofollow": false}, {"id": 15150, "name": "British Imperial and Colonial History (1600 - )", "url": "https://www.academia.edu/Documents/in/British_Imperial_and_Colonial_History_1600_-_?f_ri=1383602", "nofollow": false}, {"id": 16175, "name": "History of Linguistic Thought", "url": "https://www.academia.edu/Documents/in/History_of_Linguistic_Thought?f_ri=1383602"}, {"id": 18727, "name": "History of Imperialism", "url": "https://www.academia.edu/Documents/in/History_of_Imperialism?f_ri=1383602"}, {"id": 662820, "name": "History of Islam In the Southeast Asia", "url": "https://www.academia.edu/Documents/in/History_of_Islam_In_the_Southeast_Asia?f_ri=1383602"}, {"id": 1383602, "name": "Malayness", "url": "https://www.academia.edu/Documents/in/Malayness?f_ri=1383602"}]}, {"id": 65210807, "title": "Malay Cultural Identities: A Review", "created_at": "2021-12-20T10:52:53.031-08:00", "url": "https://www.academia.edu/65210807/Malay_Cultural_Identities_A_Review?f_ri=1383602", "dom_id": "work_65210807", "summary": null, "downloadable_attachments": [{"id": 76910320, "asset_id": 65210807, "asset_type": "Work", "always_allow_download": false}], "ordered_authors": [{"id": 210930849, "first_name": "MD SAIFUL", "last_name": "ISLAM", "domain_name": "independent", "page_name": "MDSAIFULISLAM407", "display_name": "MD SAIFUL ISLAM", "profile_url": "https://independent.academia.edu/MDSAIFULISLAM407?f_ri=1383602", "photo": "/images/s65_no_pic.png"}, {"id": 9631639, "first_name": "ruzy", "last_name": "hashim", "domain_name": "independent", "page_name": "ruzyhashim", "display_name": "ruzy hashim", "profile_url": "https://independent.academia.edu/ruzyhashim?f_ri=1383602", "photo": "https://0.academia-photos.com/9631639/10540702/11763731/s65_ruzy.hashim.jpg"}], "research_interests": [{"id": 184, "name": "Sociology", "url": "https://www.academia.edu/Documents/in/Sociology?f_ri=1383602", "nofollow": false}, {"id": 578214, "name": "Impact of Social Sciences and Humanities", "url": "https://www.academia.edu/Documents/in/Impact_of_Social_Sciences_and_Humanities?f_ri=1383602", "nofollow": false}, {"id": 1383602, "name": "Malayness", "url": "https://www.academia.edu/Documents/in/Malayness?f_ri=1383602", "nofollow": false}]}, {"id": 68510137, "title": "Malayan Muslims as a Reflection of Malayness in Anthony Burgess's Time for a Tiger", "created_at": "2022-01-17T03:13:53.026-08:00", "url": "https://www.academia.edu/68510137/Malayan_Muslims_as_a_Reflection_of_Malayness_in_Anthony_Burgesss_Time_for_a_Tiger?f_ri=1383602", "dom_id": "work_68510137", "summary": "In one of the most overlooked English literary text on the Malay\nWorld, namely Anthony Burgess\u2019 novel Time for a Tiger (1956), the\ndepictions of Islamic practices through the Malay characters show their\nhypocrisy and that they are wayward Muslims (Zawiah Yahya, 2003).\nThis paper then seeks to explore the role of Islam as a paradigm of\nMalayness in literature portrayed through characters understood to be\nMalay. The objectives of this study are met by undertaking a close\nreading of the text as a methodology to explore how the Malay\ncharacters understand and practise Islam, and to discover whether they\nconform to the Islamic beliefs as understood by non-Muslims; here, to\nBurgess\u2019 understandings of Malayan Islam. The conceptual framework\nis based on the paradigm of Malayness in literature as an everyday-\ndefined social reality consisting of six elements \u2014 the Malay language,\nIslam, the Malay rulers, adat/culture, ethnicity and identity (Ida\nBaizura Bahar, 2010) as opposed to it as an authority-defined social\nreality comprising only of Islam, the Malay language and the Malay\nrulers (Shamsul A. B., 2001). The findings demonstrate that Burgess\ncould have made an implicit criticism of Malayan Muslims by mocking\nthe reality of the Malays through his observations during his stay in\nMalaya and that the paradigm of Malayness in literature is not an\nauthority-defined but an everyday-defined social reality. Findings from\nthis study therefore can contribute to the on-going discourse on Islam\nand Malayness in literature as well as English Literature on the Malay\nWorld.", "downloadable_attachments": [{"id": 78958886, "asset_id": 68510137, "asset_type": "Work", "always_allow_download": false}], "ordered_authors": [{"id": 7907144, "first_name": "Nurhanis", "last_name": "Sahiddan", "domain_name": "uniten", "page_name": "NurhanisSahiddan", "display_name": "Nurhanis Sahiddan", "profile_url": "https://uniten.academia.edu/NurhanisSahiddan?f_ri=1383602", "photo": "https://0.academia-photos.com/7907144/2786648/60045884/s65_nurhanis.sahiddan.png"}], "research_interests": [{"id": 885, "name": "English Literature", "url": "https://www.academia.edu/Documents/in/English_Literature?f_ri=1383602", "nofollow": false}, {"id": 2860, "name": "Postcolonial Studies", "url": "https://www.academia.edu/Documents/in/Postcolonial_Studies?f_ri=1383602", "nofollow": false}, {"id": 7008, "name": "Anthony Burgess", "url": "https://www.academia.edu/Documents/in/Anthony_Burgess?f_ri=1383602", "nofollow": false}, {"id": 15863, "name": "Postcolonial Literature", "url": "https://www.academia.edu/Documents/in/Postcolonial_Literature?f_ri=1383602", "nofollow": false}, {"id": 74382, "name": "Novels", "url": "https://www.academia.edu/Documents/in/Novels?f_ri=1383602"}, {"id": 1383602, "name": "Malayness", "url": "https://www.academia.edu/Documents/in/Malayness?f_ri=1383602"}]}, {"id": 54536908, "title": "Malay Cultural Identities: A Review", "created_at": "2021-10-01T02:53:38.586-07:00", "url": "https://www.academia.edu/54536908/Malay_Cultural_Identities_A_Review?f_ri=1383602", "dom_id": "work_54536908", "summary": null, "downloadable_attachments": [{"id": 70854871, "asset_id": 54536908, "asset_type": "Work", "always_allow_download": false}], "ordered_authors": [{"id": 9631639, "first_name": "ruzy", "last_name": "hashim", "domain_name": "independent", "page_name": "ruzyhashim", "display_name": "ruzy hashim", "profile_url": "https://independent.academia.edu/ruzyhashim?f_ri=1383602", "photo": "https://0.academia-photos.com/9631639/10540702/11763731/s65_ruzy.hashim.jpg"}], "research_interests": [{"id": 1383602, "name": "Malayness", "url": "https://www.academia.edu/Documents/in/Malayness?f_ri=1383602", "nofollow": false}]}]